**4. Verify accessibility (post-generation):**
- Weasyprint **does not auto-tag** PDFs by default (v60+ adds opt-in `--presentational-hints`).
- To ensure tagged PDFs: use `--presentational-hints` **only if** you rely on HTML semantics.
- Better: use `--pdf-variant=pdf/ua-1` (PDF/UA) and validate with `@axe-core/playwright` on the rendered HTML *before* conversion.

✅ Demo-friendly tip: Show side-by-side before/after — invalid HTML (e.g., missing `alt`) produces inaccessible PDFs.

WeasyPrint supports several CSS properties to control pagination within tables. Use **`page-break-inside: avoid`** on `<tr>` and **`page-break-before: avoid`** on `<thead>` to keep headers with their data rows.

Example CSS:
```css
@media print {
  table {
    page-break-inside: avoid;
  }
  tr {
    page-break-inside: avoid;
  }
  thead {
    display: table-header-group;
    page-break-after: avoid;
    page-break-before: avoid;
  }
  tfoot {
    display: table-footer-group;
    page-break-after: avoid;
  }
}
```

Important notes:
- `display: table-header-group` ensures the header repeats on each page (if the table spans pages).
- Avoid `page-break-inside: avoid` on `<tbody>` — it may cause large gaps; prefer per-row control.
- WeasyPrint does **not** support `break-inside: avoid` reliably for tables — stick to legacy `page-break-*` properties.
- Test with varied content lengths; if rows are taller than a page, they will still overflow — consider splitting large tables manually before conversion.

